      "text": "Understanding Con Edison Rates\n\nCommercial rates education\n\n# Understanding the Basics\n\n---\n\nDiscover how your electric rates work and make informed choices to manage your energy usage.\n\n## How Your Rate Is Set\n\n---\n\nCommercial rates are based on your type of business and how much electricity you use. All small businesses start on Service Classification 2 (SC2) rates, unless the expected load is estimated to exceed 10 kW. If your account starts on SC2 (General - Small) rates and your metered peak demand usage rises above 10 kW for two months in a row, you move to SC9 (General - Large) rates that will include demand charges.\n\nSelect a service classification to learn more\n\nSelect a Rate\n\nChoose the service classification you'd like to know more about.\n\nThen choose a rate.\n\n## What's the difference? SC2 vs SC9\n\n---\n\nSC2 and SC9 are different service classifications for Con Edison commercial and industrial customers. SC2 is for smaller businesses that use less electricity, while SC9 is designed for larger sites that use more power.\n\nThe biggest difference is that SC2 Standard rate charges are based on the total amount of electricity you use (energy delivery and supply), whereas SC9 include demand charges as well.\n\nThe demand charge in SC9 means if you use lots of energy at one time (like running a lot of heavy electrical equipment), you'll pay more, even if your total monthly usage isn't that high. These rates encourage large businesses to spread out when they use the most power and reduce strain on the grid.\n\n## Deeper Dive Into Pricing Options\n\n---\n\nSC2 RateSC9 Rate\n\nStandard (SC9 Rate I)\n\n- Flat demand charge per kW based on your monthly peak\n- Energy charges per kWh used\n\nTime-of-Day, Mandatory (SC9 Rate II)\n\n- Monday through Friday, 8 a.m. to 6 p.m.\n- Monday through Friday, 8 a.m. to 10 p.m.\n- All hours of all days\n\n- Monday through Friday, 8 a.m. to 6 p.m.\n- All hours of all days\n\nTime-of-Day, Voluntary (SC9 Rate III)\n\n- Monday through Friday, 8 a.m. to 6 p.m.\n- Monday through Friday, 8 a.m. to 10 p.m.\n- All hours of all days\n\n- Monday through Friday, 8 a.m. to 6 p.m.\n- All hours of all days\n\nStandby Service (SC9 Rate IV)\n\n- Includes Energy Delivery charges, flat rate applicable to all hours, all months.\n- As-used Daily Demand Delivery Charges, per kW of Daily Peak Demand of specified time period.\n- Includes a Contract Demand charge, per kW amount that is determined prior to enrollment\n\nStandby Service, Large (SC9 Rate V)\n\n- As-used Daily Demand Delivery Charges, per kW of Daily Peak Demand of specified time period.\n- Includes a Contract Demand charge, per kW amount that is determined prior to enrollment\n\n| Pricing Name | Details | Delivery | Best For |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Straightforward demand-based rates for larger commercial customers. Your peak demand each month sets your delivery charges. | Large businesses needing basic service, not seeking time-of-day optimization. |\n| A mandatory rate for large commercial and industrial customers who have a monthly maximum demand that exceeds 1500 kW. | Largest customers subject to mandatory time-of-day billing; businesses with monthly max demand >1,500 kW |\n| Enjoy lower rates during nights and weekends but pay higher rates during business day peak hours. Great for businesses that can control when you use most of your electricity. | Large businesses who can shift or optimize usage and are not subject to mandatory SC9 Rate II. |\n| Standby plans charge based on your electricity demand during set periods of each day, offering flexibility to match your usage patterns. | Businesses with onsite generation (i.e. solar, battery, generators) and have Contract Demand less than 1500 kW. |\n| Standby plans charge based on your electricity demand during set periods of each day, offering flexibility to match your usage patterns. | Businesses with onsite generation (i.e. solar, battery, generators) and have Contract Demand greater than 1500 kW. |",
